\f0\b\fs48 \cf0 IV. Sampling
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\f2 SAMPLING 
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 Digital recording or and playback of relatively short sounds. Instead of scanning a small fixed wavetable containing one cycle of a waveform, a sampling system scans a large wavetable, usually much longer than a single audio frequency wavelength
\fs48 .
\fs32 \

\f1\fs48 \uc0\u8232 
\f2 LOOP POINTS 
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 start and end points for repeating playback
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\fs48 \uc0\u8232 
\f2 SPLICED VS. CROSSFADED LOOPS
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 clicks and thumps, envelopes at loop points
\f1\fs48 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\f2 BIDIRECTIONAL LOOPS
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 forwards/backwards
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\fs48 \uc0\u8232 
\f2 TIME-DOMAIN PITCH-SHIFTING - RESAMPLING
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 sample rate conversion
\f1\fs48 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\f2 DECIMATION-DOWNSAMPLING
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 skipping samples to raise pitch
\fs32 \

\fs48 INTERPOLATION-UPSAMPLING 
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 inserting samples to lower pitch
\f1\fs48 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\f2 GRANULAR SAMPLING
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs36 providing an envelope for each looped segment to avoid discontinuities that create clicks; loop points may be selected at random from a buffered live audio stream or from a soundfile, and then pitch-shifted. Each enveloped sample is called a grain, though this normally implies very short samples.
